What is and isn't a TT sink
This is the load-bearing fact: fetch() request bodies and XMLHttpRequest.send() payloads are NOT Trusted-Types sinks. The strict CSP does not block our outbound API calls or our SSE consumption — it only governs DOM injection. So Worker C's userscript-side fetch(url, {credentials:'include'}) is unaffected by claude.ai's strict CSP. From MDN — Trusted Types: "Trusted Types covers DOM XSS sinks: Element.innerHTML, Element.outerHTML, Document.write, Range.createContextualFragment, script element src/text/textContent, eval, setTimeout/setInterval with string args, Worker/SharedWorker URL, iframe.srcdoc. Network APIs are not covered."

DOMPurify with RETURN_TRUSTED_TYPE: true integrates natively. Mermaid output (which uses innerHTML) needs to wrap its render in a TT-aware shim or we set securityLevel: 'strict'.

worker-src blob: is required for Monaco's web workers (Monaco creates inline workers via Blob URL). frame-src blob: is required for the artifact iframe with srcdoc.

